##Missed opportunities for new crown disease in early neglected small hospital cases

Health insight

Functional introduction, understand the health professional news

* Fu Hospital, 200 meters from the South China Seafood Market, in December 2019 received 3 patients with "pneumonia of unknown cause" , including the first confirmed case later referred to Jinyintan Hospital.
* At the beginning of the epidemic, the doctors in the small hospitals were not taken seriously in the epidemiological investigation made by the disease control departments at all levels, which may lead to the error of the early diagnosis standard of NCP.
* In early May, Youfu Hospital found that medical staff and in-patients infected, but because there is no market contact history in south China, does not meet the diagnostic criteria, did not report.
* On April 20,10 days later, Zhong Nanshan declared a new case of "human-to-human" pneumonia.

Youfu Hospital, 200 meters away from the South China Seafood Market, received 3 patients with "pneumonia of unknown cause" in December 2019, including the first confirmed case later referred to Jinyintan Hospital.

At the beginning of the epidemic, doctors in small hospitals were not taken seriously in the epidemiological investigations carried out by the disease control departments at all levels, which may have led to the failure of early diagnostic criteria for NCP.

In early January, Youfu Hospital found that medical staff and in-patients infected, but because there is no history of exposure to the south China market, does not meet the diagnostic criteria, did not report.

On January 20,10 days later, Zhong Nanshan declared a new case of "human-to-human" pneumonia.

On December 12,2019, Liu Yong (not his real name) , an out-patient doctor at Wuhan Special Care Hospital, received a patient with a somewhat strange condition. So that nearly two months later, the mention of this patient, his condition at that time, said every word, Liu Yong remembered extremely clearly.

The patient's symptoms were not severe, but unlike the usual flu this season: A dry cough, but no fever, and no runny nose. The patient said that he was a merchant in the south China Seafood Market. Seven or eight employees of the shop next door had a high fever for several days. They had a dry cough. The whole shop was empty. They were worried that they might be infected, so they came for tests.

Looking back now, this is probably one of the earliest cases of NCP.

Wuhan Youfu Hospital is a second-level general hospital mainly for mental health, only 200 meters away from the South China Seafood Market. More than 2,000 businesses and nearby residents of the south China seafood market formed part of the crowd that came to the hospital for medical treatment, they will also head to another nearby hospital, the Wuhan Red Cross Hospital, and a top three hospital -- a combination of traditional Chinese and Western medicine in Hubei Province.

![img](data:image/jpeg;base64,)
PICTURE: screenshot from mobile phone

By mid-december, the three hospitals began to find patients with different symptoms of seasonal flu: Many had no fever, just a dry cough, but significant lung lesions.

Fever clinics in small hospitals were unable to confirm the cases and doctors advised them to be transferred to another hospital. On December 27, one of the first new patients diagnosed with pneumonia in Wuhan Jinyintan Hospital was referred from Youfu Hospital.

Most patients who do not have a fever do not choose to go to the four major hospitals in Wuhan, such as Xiehe, Tongji, China-South Africa and Renmin, which have the most powerful local medical resources. And the four major hospitals to receive patients, mostly in the transfer clinic, the second-level hospital, high fever does not retreat, there are serious pneumonia symptoms of the patient.

This means that these small hospitals, on the contrary, are the first large hospital contact with new pneumonia patients in the hospital.

Some of the doctors working at these hospitals are acutely aware of the abnormalities in these cases. But at the beginning of the outbreak, the disease control departments at all levels of epidemiological investigations and interviews, these doctors are not taken seriously, which is likely to lead to new pneumonia early diagnostic criteria error.

"The CDC should pay attention to us as front-line clinicians, especially when new pandemics are emerging, " lamented one of the hospital's doctors.

![img](data:image/jpeg;base64,)
A hospital emergency room in Wuhan, photo by Wu Jing

The first patients: not necessarily fever,

There is not necessarily a history of contact with the south China Seafood Market

On December 12, when Liu Yong was on duty, fewer people came to the clinic than usual. A 69 year old patient, surnamed Huang, came to the clinic voluntarily for consultation.

Liu Yong studied infectious diseases, huang MOU says"next door 78 employee have a fever suddenly", let him begin vigilance all of a sudden, suggest patient makes a CT examination. Huang felt that her symptoms were not serious, and she refused to go to Florida, which is what many people think. Some of the seafood market traders, accustomed to seeing doctors in small clinics and hospitals, were reluctant to spend money on tests they didn't think were necessary.

Since unwilling to check, Liu Yong suggested going to the nearby Wuhan Red Cross Hospital or Xinhua hospital to have a look. Because these two hospitals have a fever clinic open all year round, higher protection facilities than the Hospital of special care. Liu Yong sensed that this might be a highly contagious disease. He worries that the hospital's simple outpatient facilities, completely can not withstand a strong infectious disease.

Liu Yong's vigilance comes from her high school experience. He has been concerned about infectious diseases ever since the villagers of his hometown, who were first mistaken for upper respiratory tract infection and were treated for the common cold and many died. He wasn't sure 100 percent of the virus came from the south China Seafood Market, but that combined with what Huang said meant at least a sudden, concentrated outbreak of the disease in the south China Seafood Market.

The next day (13 December) was a Friday, and as soon as he arrived at work, Liu Yong reminded his colleagues that everyone who came to see a doctor at the south China Seafood Market would be provided with a general surgical mask free of charge. He also advised all doctors in radiology and outpatient departments to wear face masks.

On December 16, another case emerged. Liu Yong's colleague interviewed a Jingzhou man from Hubei Province who always came to the south China seafood market. The patient, a 70-year-old man, had been feverish for several days and presented with retching. On the same day, a blood test, no abnormalities, was judged to be upper respiratory tract infection, colleagues worried about the flu, prescribed the flu drug Oseltamivir. Two days after the infusion, his symptoms didn't improve. The doctor advised him to do a CT, he felt 213 yuan a CT is not worth, refused, only done a 79 yuan chest radiograph, but chest radiograph did not see anything abnormal.

The doctor advised the patient to be transferred to Wuhan Red Cross Hospital. The patient was later contacted by Jianwen at 8 o'clock. He was diagnosed with a lung infection at Wuhan Red Cross Hospital and was hospitalized for seven days, but did not get better. On December 24, he went to Tongji Hospital, where he was diagnosed with new crown pneumonia. He was cured before the city was closed on January 23 and returned to his home in Jingzhou.

According to the case search and retrospective investigation carried out at that time, the case of the earliest onset of the disease was similar to that of this patient in the circular on unexplained pneumonia issued by Wuhan Municipal Health and Health Commission on January 5,2020.

After discussion, doctors at the Special Care Hospital decided on a test plan for "unlike regular flu" patients. Routine blood tests and chest X-RAYS did not show any abnormalities and a CT scan was required. From this case, doctors at the Outpatient Department of the Special Care Hospital have formed a consensus: If patients do not do CT, doctors do not make a diagnosis.

On December 27, a third patient with a similar condition appeared. He did not have a fever, just a cough, he spent years in the south China seafood market procurement goods, because see around many businesses fever, some fear, their own initiative to do a physical examination. Even though he did not have a fever, doctors at the Special Care Hospital performed a CT scan on him according to the principles just discussed. However, they found that the patient, who was not feverish at the time, had severe abnormalities in his lungs. They diagnosed him as "pneumonia" and recommended that he be hospitalized for treatment. After two days of treatment, on December 29, doctors referred him to Wuhan Jinyintan Hospital. The patient became one of the first to be diagnosed with a nucleic acid test at Wuhan Jinyintan hospital.

After receiving these three patients, the doctors in the Special Care Hospital felt that it was not easy for their own hospital to solve the problem. They decided internally that if they encountered such patients again, they would be the first to recommend referral to a higher-level hospital.

Meanwhile, Doctor Zhang Jixian of Hubei Integrated Traditional Chinese and Western Medicine Hospital near Youfu Hospital also found this kind of case. According to media reports, on December 26,2019, an old couple from a neighborhood near the hospital came to the integrated Chinese and Western Medicine Hospital for treatment due to fever and cough. The chest CT film taken showed a completely different change from other viral pneumonia. Zhang Jixian let the old couple call their son also do a test, no symptoms of the son, a CT, the lungs have that performance.

The next day, she reported the trio's condition and another similar case from the south China Seafood Market to the hospital, which immediately reported them to the Kong Hon CDC. Zhang Jixian became the first person to report the new Crown Disease in Wuhan.

According to the clinicians who were the first to contact patients with NCP in these special care hospitals, fever is not a necessary symptom of this new type of pneumonia, and Zhang Jixian found that not all cases had a history of exposure to the south China seafood market.

![img](data:image/jpeg;base64,)
Injection Room of a hospital in Wuhan, photo by Wu Jing

In early January, "human-to-human" phenomenon already exists

December 31, Wuhan Health Commission issued the first public "unexplained pneumonia" epidemic notice. National Health Commission sent a group of experts to Wuhan, Wuhan Jinyintan Hospital Research, and then developed a unexplained pneumonia cases report three criteria, 1, there is a history of contact with the South China Seafood Market; 2, Fever; 3, CT, rule Out Mycoplasma, chlamydia, and other infections.

The day before, the medical and Medical Administration Department of the Wuhan Health Commission issued a notice that patients with pneumonia of unknown cause had appeared in the south China Seafood Market One after another, and that patients with pneumonia of unknown cause who had been seen in the past week were immediately screened.

According to Liu Yong, some of the first patients to go to golden pond were transferred from the three hospitals closest to the south China Seafood Market, most of them with a history of exposure to the market. By the time he is transferred to the hospital, the condition may have developed for some time, which may affect the experts'judgment.

At the same time, one doctor recalled, the Wuhan Health and Safety Commission had sent several messages to hospitals: 1, it's not SARS; 2, it's not human to human; 3, it's not going to kill the patient; and 4, it's not going to infect the staff. So much so that after the closure of the south China seafood market on December 31st, some hospitals were saying that they thought it was a little over the top and making a big deal out of it.

However, they were shocked by what happened.

In early January 2020, pneumonia of unknown cause was named Covid-19, and even doctors at Yu Fu hospital recommended referral for such cases, however, some of the hospital staff and the first ward, the third ward psychiatric patients, but there is a concentrated fever, dry cough symptoms.

The hospitalized psychiatric patients had no direct exposure history to the south China seafood market. After the doctor's consultation, combined with the example of the first consultation in Youfu Hospital in December before, the patients who were diagnosed as new coronary pneumonia after being referred to other hospitals all had a history of contact with the south China Seafood Market, the conclusion is that the hospital is too close to the south China seafood market, some of the patients'relatives brought the virus into the hospital when they visited the in-patients. This means that the virus "human-to-human" phenomenon exists.

The hospital didn't have a DNA test, so we don't know if it's coronavirus. But according to the three diagnostic criteria previously given by experts for suspected cases, most of the patients with fever in such concentrated outbreaks had no history of exposure to the south China seafood market, so they did not report the cases at the time as pneumonia of unknown origin.

Looking back now, the above three criteria for reporting suspected cases are not reasonable. Many patients do not have a history of exposure to the south China market, and many patients do not have fever in the outpatient department. According to the latest research paper by Academician Zhong Nanshan's team, a study of 1,099 newly diagnosed patients with pneumonia in 552 hospitals in 31 provinces and cities across the country showed that 43.8% of patients presented with fever symptoms at the time of admission, however, 87.9% developed fever and 15.7% developed severe pneumonia after hospitalization.

In early January, the head of a department at Youfu Hospital was diagnosed with new coronary pneumonia. He was admitted to Wuhan Central Hospital, where he requested isolation treatment and was eventually transferred to Golden Pond Hospital in serious condition.

At the same time, a group of medical workers were alerted and notified by the Wuhan Public Security Bureau for "publishing false statements on the Internet, " which reached Feng Yun (not his real name) , director of the Special Care Hospital.

When several things came together, Feng Yun sensed something was wrong and went to the fever clinic, the Laboratory, and the radiology departments to gather information. After consulting with the hospital's leaders, he decided to invite the director of another hospital to summarize and analyze the cases.

On the morning of January 17, the director of another hospital, after a consultation, concluded that it was the viral pneumonia, not the bacterial pneumonia. This is also in line with the original Liu Yong's judgment: "The bacterial pneumonia can not spread so fast in the short term, it should be viral pneumonia. "

January 17 that day is a small year, the hospital was to hold a Spring Festival party, the temporary decision to cancel the afternoon activities, began to build isolation ward.

The reporting mechanism was not working properly and Zhong Nanshan announced that it was 10 days later

Although cases of hospitalized patients did not meet the CDC's initial three criteria and were not reported for pneumonia of unknown cause, but the hospital still on January 10 or so to the hospital staff and patients concentrated fever to the higher CDC Department.

According to the recollection of a doctor in the Special Care Hospital, at that time, the higher disease control authorities did not immediately come to the hospital to conduct research, instead, he asked them: "You have not been exposed to the south China Seafood Market, why do you have this disease? " The hospital sent back three cases initially treated by physicians to its higher-level Disease Control Department, which neither confirmed nor denied them.

On January 12, the CDC began issuing documents and forms to hospitals, asking them to report fever in their outpatient clinics. It was initially required to be reported before 4 p.m. , but gradually changed to 8 p.m. to 10 p.m.

On January 17, the criteria for reporting suspected cases of new coronary pneumonia were relaxed and did not require a history of exposure to the south China seafood market. Youfu Hospital began to report a large number of cases to the Department of Disease Control, all of a sudden reported 30 fever patients.

On January 18, members of the senior Expert Group of the National Health Commission again came to Wuhan to investigate. This time, the research subjects included experts from the four major hospitals, including Zhongnan Hospital and People's Hospital. During the investigation, the four major hospitals reported the infection situation of their medical staff, the request of lowering the diagnostic standard of suspected cases was put forward again.

On January 18th, the CDC added a case of infection among health care workers to the hospital's report form.

On January 20th Zhong Nanshan, head of the State Council's high-level panel, called the new coronavirus "human-to-human" . At this time, from the hospital to find the hospital staff and hospital patients with infection, has passed 10 days.

After January 20, the number of confirmed and suspected cases rose sharply in Wuhan, from 41 announced a month ago to nearly 20,000 on February 10. More than 40,000 people have been confirmed nationwide as human-to-human transmission has spread to other areas.

Doctors at the Special Care Hospital are thankful that only 16 medical staff members have been infected, which is relatively mild among medical staff at hospitals in Wuhan. And in mid-december, four radiologists began taking precautions, none of whom was infected. In addition, while there are 86 confirmed and suspected patients who can not be transferred, a significant proportion of them are mentally ill and no hospital is willing to admit them. But these patients were quarantined early on in a new building at the hospital.

On February 7th, doctors from the Special Care Hospital were interviewed by the CDC. The CDC believes they underreported cases in late December and early January. The doctor objected: "The health commission required three conditions at the same time to report, did not meet these three conditions. "

"If we had paid attention to the small hospitals in the concentrated areas of the epidemic, and trusted the reports and judgments of our clinicians, maybe the situation would not have developed to this point, " one doctor lamented.
